<br>
1. Determination of what a &quot;Unscheduled&quot; outage is.  Limited notice of a patch is to me Unscheduled.  This includes those patches called scheduled, but are announced only a day or two before.<br>
<br>
2. I also think, as we are requiring this board be used as the scheduling tool, that the patches be posted on the Home Page or noted on the banner.  Going several places for this information each day is unacceptable.<br>
<br>
3. Individuals/Guilds are given 48 hours, from when notified on the board (Dragon falls or conceded and the notification is posted), to post their intention.<br>
<br>
4. The extension should be dependant on a few variables.  Unscheduled outages, based upon the modified definition, receive a five (5) day window to perform the raid unless one of the following conditions are met:<br>
<br>
A. If the scheduled raid date is not impacted by an Unscheduled Patch, then the scheduled date stands.  e.g. Raid is scheduled on a Saturday and a Unscheduled patch occurs on a Friday.  The raider MUST take down the Dragon on Saturday, as there will be no impact to them.  They should not be allowed to extend from the initial time they had intended.<br>
<br>
B. If the Unscheduled patch occurs on a Friday or Saturday, or any day prior to the last day of multi-day Holiday, then the raid is given 48 Hours to compete the raid. e.g. If a patch happens on a Friday, then they MUST take down the Dragon by that Sunday unless part A is met.<br>
<br>
C. If the window of 5 days contains a weekend or holiday, then they must host the raid no later than the first FULL weekend or holiday day, unless it occurs on a Friday in which case part C would be in effect. (Friday, Saturday and Sunday considered weekend days, Saturday and Sunday FULL weekend days).  e.g. A patch happens on a Thursday, they must take the Dragon down no later than Saturday evening unless part A is met -OR- A patch happens on a Sunday, and Monday is a holiday .. The dragon must be taken down by Monday evening.<br>
<br>
<br>
-----------------<br>
<br>
This option does four things.<br>
<br>
1. It only extends the proposed &quot;72 hour starting the first full day after a patch&quot; if it occurs on a Sunday, Monday, or Tuesay (and the day following is not a holiday) and permits the raiders the ability to host the raid on the weekend UNLESS their scheduled date was prior.<br>
<br>
2. Reduces the amount of rescheduling that has to occur.  Basically no rescheduling needs to occur unless scheduled for a Sunday and a patch happens on the previous Monday, their initial raid date stands -OR- the patch occurs on a the date scheduled. I do agree with some of the posts here in that folks can be gathered rather quickly.  What I don't agree is that can occur easily on a weekday and that there is no impact .. there are other raids folks are signed up for or leading, so there can and normally is impact.  Should we leave Fear open because of this?  I think not.<br>
<br>
3. Variablizes the extension, in such that if there is no impact to the initially scheduled date nothing changes.  Why should folks get MORE time to do a raid because of a patch.<br>
<br>
4. Allows some flexibility in that weekends and holidays are treated with higher priority and if there is a valid opportunity to take the Dragon down on one they must do so.<br>
<br>
-------------------<br>
<br>
Also, I belive that FG's and Naggy should be scheduled separately.  However, Naggy raids should have priority and be able to set the date and time they choose, within the bounds of their time period.  It is not acceptable to force a schedule on a Dragon, then tell them they are at the mercy of another raid.  NO, it is not acceptable for them to wait or to have both sets of raids going on at the same time.  FG raids should not be allowed to occur within 8 Hours (or 6 .. whatever the exact repop time it) of the Naggy raid to limit the possibility of FG's popping on the Naggy Raid.  These issues open the raid to failure, lag, and un-required risks.<br>
<br>
